-\begin{theorem}[Transfer-Graph Overlap]
-\label{thm:overlap}
-For Givens-type sector transfers $T_{i\to j}$ and $T_{k\to l}$ acting on the BDG sector space, $[T_{i\to j},T_{k\to l}]=0$ if and only if $\{i,j\}\cap\{k,l\}=\emptyset$. Verified exhaustively by direct computation for $n=2,3,4,5,6$ in \texttt{berry\_theorems.py}. The Berry geometry is therefore controlled by the incidence structure of the sector transfer graph.
-\end{theorem}
-
-\begin{theorem}[Exact Poisson-thinning transfer law]
-\label{thm:thinning}
-The conditional probability that a boundary-event promotes the local motif to depth-$k$ sector is $f_k=\lambda_k/\sum_j\lambda_j$ exactly (not approximately), where $\lambda_k=\mu^k/k!$ are the Poisson-CSG rates at density $\mu$. This is a consequence of the Poisson thinning property: in a Poisson process partitioned into regions with rates $\{\lambda_k\}$, a uniformly random point falls in region $k$ with probability exactly $\lambda_k/\sum_j\lambda_j$, and region counts are independent Poisson variables. The BDG transfer fractions therefore require no modeling assumption beyond the Poisson-CSG framework of Paper~I.
-\end{theorem}
-
-\begin{theorem}[2-sector flatness]
-\label{thm:2sector}
-For any 2-sector BDG transfer system, the Berry phase is identically zero. By Theorem~\ref{thm:overlap}, the two transfers overlap on both indices; the resulting rotations act about the same axis in the relevant $\mathrm{SU}(2)$ Lie algebra, and same-axis rotations commute. The Wilson-loop eigenphase equals the sum of the individual rotation phases---a dynamical total phase, not a geometric one.
-\end{theorem}
-
-\begin{theorem}[Minimum curved sector count $=3$]
-\label{thm:min3}
-Nonzero Berry phase requires a minimum of 3 BDG depth sectors. The three BDG phase kicks around any 3-cycle of the sector graph sum to zero but are unequal in magnitude (all six pairs $|c_{j}-c_i|$ for the BDG coefficients $(c_1,c_2,c_3,c_4)=(-1,9,-16,8)$ produce six distinct values $|10|,|25|,|24|,|15|,|1|,|9|$); by Theorem~\ref{thm:overlap} the adjacent transfers overlap on one index and do not commute. Combined with Theorem~\ref{thm:2sector}, this establishes that 3 is the minimum sector count for genuine geometric phase.
-\end{theorem}
-
-\begin{theorem}[Depth-3 curvature maximum]
-\label{thm:depth3max}
-The strongest Berry curvature contributions come from transitions involving depth $k=3$ (coefficient $c_3=-16$, the largest in magnitude), producing kicks $|\Delta_{23}|=25$ and $|\Delta_{34}|=24$. Since $|c_3|$ exceeds the next-largest $|c_k|$ by $\ge 7$, any plaquette involving depth 3 carries curvature strictly larger than any plaquette not involving depth 3.
